// ══ MMI STATIONS ══
const MMI_STATIONS=[
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"You are sitting in an MMI at a leading Australian medical school. The examiner looks up from their notes and says: 'Tell me why you want to study medicine. And please — avoid the clichés.'",prompt1:"Why do you want to study medicine?",prompt2:"What has your path to this interview taught you about yourself?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a medical student on placement. You observe your supervising consultant dismiss a patient's concerns about a proposed treatment with visible impatience, saying 'Trust me, I've done this a thousand times.' The patient looks uncertain but says nothing more. The treatment plan proceeds.",prompt1:"What are your thoughts on what just happened?",prompt2:"What, if anything, would you do — and how do you weigh speaking up against the risk of undermining a senior colleague?"},
{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"You are a medical student. The examiner will play the role of a close friend, Jamie, who has called you clearly upset. Jamie says: 'I don't know what to do — I've been feeling completely hopeless lately and I haven't told anyone. I needed to tell someone I trust.'",prompt1:"[Role-play] Respond to Jamie as you would in this real conversation.",prompt2:"[Reflect] What made this conversation difficult, and what do you think Jamie needed most from you?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a third-year medical student on a clinical team. A nurse pulls you aside and tells you that she believes the registrar made an error in a patient's medication order. She is hesitant to raise it herself and asks you to 'look into it.' The registrar is known for being dismissive when challenged.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"What does this situation reveal about the role of hierarchy in patient safety, and how should healthcare teams manage it?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner presents you with the following scenario: A government body is considering a policy that would require all medical students to complete a mandatory rural placement of at least 12 months before graduating, in response to the critical shortage of doctors in regional Australia.",prompt1:"What do you see as the strongest arguments for and against this policy?",prompt2:"How do you think medical schools should balance producing specialists for cities versus generalists for rural communities?"},
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'You've listed significant volunteer work in your application. I want to understand it more deeply. What did you actually learn from it — not what you were supposed to learn, but what genuinely surprised you or changed the way you think?'",prompt1:"What did your volunteer experience genuinely teach you?",prompt2:"How has it shaped what kind of doctor you want to be?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"A patient in her mid-30s is admitted following a suicide attempt. She is medically stable and coherent. She tells you clearly that she does not want her family notified, and she does not want any psychiatric intervention. 'I know my own mind,' she says. 'I just want to go home.'",prompt1:"What are the ethical tensions in this situation?",prompt2:"How do you balance a patient's right to autonomy with a duty of care — and is there ever a point where that balance tips decisively one way?"},
{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner will play a patient, Mr. Chen, a 72-year-old man who has been told by his oncologist that his cancer is no longer responding to treatment. He has come to speak with you — a junior doctor — because his oncologist was busy and he has questions. He says: 'I just want someone to be straight with me. How long do I have?'",prompt1:"[Role-play] Respond to Mr. Chen.",prompt2:"[Reflect] What made this conversation particularly challenging, and how do you think about the difference between honesty and hope in end-of-life care?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a member of a student research group. Over several months, you notice that one member — a high achiever who is well-liked by the supervisor — consistently takes more credit than is due in group presentations and written reports, while another quieter member whose contributions are substantial is consistently uncredited. Neither has raised it.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Why do you think the uncredited member hasn't raised it themselves — and what does that tell you about the dynamics at play?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'There is an ongoing debate about whether medical school interviews — including the MMI format — are effective at selecting the best future doctors. Some researchers argue they favour candidates who are coached, articulate, and socioculturally advantaged. What do you think?'",prompt1:"What is your view on whether the MMI is an effective selection tool?",prompt2:"If you were designing a fairer admissions process, what would it look like?"}

// ── 50 NEW MMI STATIONS ──
// MOTIVATION (10)
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'A lot of applicants tell me they want to be a doctor because they want to make a difference. But doctors who burn out also wanted to make a difference. What makes you think you'll last?'",prompt1:"What do you think will sustain you through the hardest parts of a medical career?",prompt2:"Describe a time in your life when you were under sustained pressure — not a single crisis, but a prolonged period of difficulty. How did you actually cope, and what does that tell you about your resilience?"}
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'Tell me about a time you encountered suffering — not in a clinical setting, just in life — and what it asked of you.'",prompt1:"Describe the experience and how you responded.",prompt2:"Looking back, is there anything you wish you had done differently — and what does that reflection tell you about the kind of practitioner you want to become?"}
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'Medicine will ask you to see people at their most vulnerable every single day. What in your background has actually prepared you for that — not in theory, but in practice?'",prompt1:"What experiences have genuinely prepared you for sustained exposure to human suffering and vulnerability?",prompt2:"Describe a specific moment when someone was at their most vulnerable in front of you — not a clinical moment, just a human one — and tell me what you did, and what it asked of you emotionally."}
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'I want you to tell me about a failure — something you genuinely got wrong, where you bore real responsibility. Not a disguised success story.'",prompt1:"What was the failure, and what was your role in it?",prompt2:"Describe what you specifically changed about the way you work or think as a direct result of that failure — not the lesson in the abstract, but the actual behavioural shift."}
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner looks at your application and says: 'You've had a fairly linear path to this interview. What has challenged you — not externally, but internally? What have you had to work to overcome in yourself?'",prompt1:"What personal quality or tendency has been your greatest challenge to manage?",prompt2:"Give me a concrete example of a situation where that internal challenge actively affected something you did or how you behaved. What happened, and what did it cost you or teach you?"}
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'Most people who sit in this chair have wanted to be a doctor for a long time. But wanting something for a long time isn't the same as being suited to it. What evidence do you have — not just desire, but actual evidence — that you are suited to this work?'",prompt1:"What evidence do you have that you are genuinely suited to medicine — beyond wanting it?",prompt2:"Give me an example of a specific interaction or experience — not a placement, but something from real life — that revealed something about yourself that you believe is directly relevant to how you will practise medicine."}
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'If medicine didn't exist as a career — if it simply wasn't an option — what would you be doing, and why?'",prompt1:"What would you be doing instead, and what does that reveal about what drives you?",prompt2:"What does your answer tell you about whether your motivation for medicine is about the work itself, or about something else?"}
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'I want to understand your relationship with uncertainty. Medicine is full of situations where you won't know the answer, where the evidence is unclear, where reasonable people disagree. How do you actually handle not knowing?'",prompt1:"How do you personally relate to uncertainty — intellectually and emotionally?",prompt2:"Give me a specific example of a time you had to act or make a decision under genuine uncertainty — where the right answer wasn't clear and the stakes were real. What did you do, and what did it teach you?"}
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'Tell me about someone — not a famous doctor, not a textbook figure — a real person in your life who has shaped how you think about medicine or healthcare.'",prompt1:"Who is this person, and what specifically have they shown you?",prompt2:"How has knowing them changed what you think a good doctor actually looks like?"}
,{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'You're applying to one of the most competitive programs in the country. But competition isn't a reason to do something — it's just a filter. Strip away the status, the difficulty, the prestige. Why this, really?'",prompt1:"What is your honest, unguarded answer for why you want to be a doctor?",prompt2:"What would it mean to you personally — not professionally — to become one?"}

// ETHICS (10)
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a final-year medical student on placement. You discover that a fellow student — someone you consider a friend — has been systematically exaggerating their clinical log entries, claiming procedures they observed but did not perform. They are due to graduate next month. No patient has been harmed.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Your friend says: 'These logs are just a bureaucratic box-tick — no one even reads them. You're going to ruin my career over nothing.' How do you respond?"}
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a junior doctor. A patient — a 55-year-old man recovering from a cardiac procedure — asks you directly: 'My wife has been asking the nurses about my condition. I'd like you to make sure no one tells her anything.' You have already spoken briefly with the wife, who is clearly anxious and involved in his care.",prompt1:"How do you respond to the patient in this moment?",prompt2:"What does this situation reveal about the tension between patient confidentiality and family-centred care?"}
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a GP. A patient you have known for five years — a 40-year-old truck driver — presents with a new diagnosis of epilepsy. He is on a treatment plan and his seizures are not yet controlled. He tells you he has not informed his employer and does not intend to, because he will lose his job. He is the primary income earner for his family.",prompt1:"What are your obligations in this situation?",prompt2:"How do you weigh a patient's privacy and livelihood against potential risk to others?"}
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a medical student. During a ward round, the consultant refers to a patient — a large Indigenous woman — as 'another one of those' under his breath, audible only to the student group. The patient does not appear to have heard. The consultant continues the round.",prompt1:"What do you do in this moment and afterward?",prompt2:"What does this kind of language — quiet, deniable, habitual — do to patients, to teams, and to the culture of medicine?"}
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"A 16-year-old girl attends your clinic alone. She is 10 weeks pregnant. She tells you she has decided to have a termination and asks for a referral. She does not want her parents to know. Your own personal values are in conflict with termination.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How do you practise medicine in areas where your personal values and your professional obligations are in genuine tension?"}
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a junior doctor. A patient's family approaches you privately and offers a cash gift — a substantial one — in gratitude for the care you provided their mother, who has now been discharged. They are warm, sincere, and clearly not trying to influence future care.",prompt1:"How do you respond to the family in this moment?",prompt2:"Where does gratitude end and a conflict of interest begin — and who decides?"}
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a medical student on a rural placement. The GP you are working with is the only doctor within 60km. You observe that he is regularly seeing patients while visibly fatigued — he has disclosed to you privately that he has been sleeping poorly for months due to a personal crisis. You have seen him make two minor errors that were caught before reaching patients.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How do you think about the ethics of a system that places one person in a position where their failure becomes a patient safety risk?"}
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a first-year resident. A patient — a devout Jehovah's Witness — refuses a blood transfusion that your team believes is necessary to survive a post-surgical bleed. She is conscious, alert, and has capacity. She is 34 years old and has two young children. Her husband, present at the bedside, is also a Jehovah's Witness and is supporting her decision.",prompt1:"How does your team proceed, and what is your role?",prompt2:"Is there any circumstance in which you believe it would be ethically justified to override her decision?"}
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a medical student. You discover that your university's anatomy department has been using cadavers donated for medical education in a commercial research partnership with a private company — a use that was not disclosed to donors or their families at the time of donation.",prompt1:"What are the ethical problems with this situation?",prompt2:"Who bears responsibility, and what should happen?"}
,{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a GP. A parent brings in their 7-year-old son requesting a referral for ADHD assessment and medication. The child is bright and active in the consultation. The parent says he is 'impossible to manage' and his teacher has 'suggested ADHD.' You have concerns about whether this is a clinical presentation or a mismatch between the child's temperament and his environment.",prompt1:"How do you approach this consultation?",prompt2:"What are the ethical dimensions of diagnosing and medicating children for behavioural concerns?"}

// ROLE-PLAY (10)
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner will play a patient, Mrs. Okafor, a 68-year-old woman who has just been told by her oncologist that her breast cancer has returned after three years of remission. She has come to see you — her GP — because she 'just needed to talk to someone she knows.' She sits down and says nothing. She is looking at her hands.",prompt1:"[Role-play] Begin the consultation.",prompt2:"[Reflect] What did this patient need from you that was different from what an oncologist would provide — and what does that tell you about the role of the GP in cancer care?"}
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner plays a 17-year-old patient, Liam, who has been brought in by his mother for a routine check-up. The mother steps out at your request. Once alone, Liam says: 'She doesn't know I'm here for anything other than a check-up. I need to talk to someone about something.' He pauses. 'I think I might be gay. I haven't told anyone.'",prompt1:"[Role-play] Respond to Liam.",prompt2:"[Reflect] What specific risks and vulnerabilities is a young person in Liam's position facing — and what does a clinician need to be aware of that goes beyond the immediate conversation?"}
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner plays a 78-year-old man, Arthur, who has been living alone since his wife died eighteen months ago. He has come in for a blood pressure check, but as you go to take his BP, he says: 'You know, I don't think I mind much about dying anymore. I'm not in a hurry, but I don't mind.' He says it matter-of-factly, looking out the window.",prompt1:"[Role-play] Respond to Arthur.",prompt2:"[Reflect] How do you distinguish between grief, existential acceptance, and clinical concern — and what does this conversation ask of you as a clinician?"}
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner plays a mother, Diane, who has brought her 12-year-old daughter in after the school contacted her about the daughter's dramatic weight loss. Diane is defensive from the moment she sits down: 'I don't know why the school called you. She eats fine at home. I think she's just growing.' Her daughter is sitting beside her, looking at the floor.",prompt1:"[Role-play] Conduct this consultation.",prompt2:"[Reflect] How do you speak to the daughter's possible experience without alienating the mother — and what are the clinical and safeguarding considerations here?"}
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner plays a 45-year-old man, Marcus, who is a firefighter. He has come in for what he described as 'just a check-up.' As you talk, it becomes clear he hasn't slept properly in months, is drinking more than usual, and had a significant incident at work three months ago that he 'doesn't want to get into.' He says he is fine. He looks tired.",prompt1:"[Role-play] Continue the consultation.",prompt2:"[Reflect] What is Marcus likely experiencing, and what are the particular barriers that make it difficult for men in high-risk occupations to seek help?"}
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner plays a 30-year-old woman, Sophie, who comes in seeking a prescription for sleeping tablets. She has been on them for two years, prescribed by another GP who has retired. She says: 'I just need them to function. I've tried stopping and I can't sleep at all without them. Please don't make this harder than it needs to be.'",prompt1:"[Role-play] Conduct this consultation.",prompt2:"[Reflect] What are the clinical and ethical considerations in this situation — and how do you maintain the therapeutic relationship when you need to say something the patient doesn't want to hear?"}
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner plays an angry father, Mr. Nguyen, who has brought his 8-year-old son in after the child was given a vaccine at school without what Mr. Nguyen considers adequate consent. He is furious: 'You people just do whatever you want. Nobody asked me. He's my son.' He is speaking loudly.",prompt1:"[Role-play] Respond to Mr. Nguyen.",prompt2:"[Reflect] What is this father's underlying concern — beneath the anger — and how does understanding that change how you approach the conversation?"}
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner plays a patient, James, 52, who has come in for his annual diabetic review. His HbA1c has worsened significantly. As you begin to discuss this, he says: 'Look, I know what you're going to say. I've heard it a hundred times. I'm not doing the diet, I'm not going on insulin, and I don't want a lecture. Just tell me what I absolutely have to know and let me go.'",prompt1:"[Role-play] Continue the consultation.",prompt2:"[Reflect] How do you respect a patient's stated wishes while still discharging your duty of care — and what does patient autonomy actually mean when someone is making choices that will harm them?"}
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner plays a 22-year-old woman, Aisha, a university student who comes in presenting with fatigue and low mood. In taking her history, you discover she has recently arrived in Australia from another country, lives alone, has few friends here, and is struggling academically. She says: 'I'm not depressed. I'm just adjusting. Please don't put that on my file.'",prompt1:"[Role-play] Continue the consultation.",prompt2:"[Reflect] What are the cultural, social, and clinical dimensions of Aisha's presentation — and how do you balance her concerns about stigma with appropriate care?"}
,{category:"Role-Play",scenario:"The examiner plays a 60-year-old patient, Bob, who has been told he needs a colonoscopy following blood in his stool. He is refusing: 'I've heard what they do in those things. No one is doing that to me. I'd rather not know.' He crossed his arms when he sat down.",prompt1:"[Role-play] Respond to Bob.",prompt2:"[Reflect] What is Bob actually afraid of — and how do you have a conversation about a potentially life-saving investigation with someone who has closed the door before you've opened it?"}

// CONFLICT RESOLUTION (10)
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a junior doctor on a busy surgical ward. The ward clerk — a long-standing staff member who is well-liked — has been consistently prioritising certain patients' discharge paperwork over others in a way that delays discharges for patients from a particular cultural background. You are not certain this is intentional. Two nurses have quietly mentioned it to you.",prompt1:"How do you approach this situation?",prompt2:"How do you address a pattern of behaviour that may or may not be deliberate — when raising it risks labelling someone unfairly, but not raising it risks harm continuing?"}
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a medical student. Your study group of five is preparing for finals. One member, Tom, has suggested you all pool and share answers to past exam questions in a shared document. The document is growing — it is now also including specific questions that Tom says he 'heard were definitely on the paper from someone who did it last year.' Two members are enthusiastic. Two are uncomfortable. Everyone is looking at you.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How do group dynamics make it harder to act on your values in these situations — and what does it take to hold your position when the group is moving in a different direction?"}
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a resident. Your registrar, whom you respect and have a good relationship with, gives you feedback after a ward round that you felt was inaccurate and publicly delivered in a way that was humiliating. Other team members were present. You are still processing it.",prompt1:"How do you handle this?",prompt2:"What is the difference between feedback that is hard to hear and feedback that is genuinely unfair — and how do you respond to each?"}
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are part of a multidisciplinary team managing an elderly patient's care. The patient's son — who has medical power of attorney — is insisting on continuing aggressive treatment. The medical team, the palliative care team, and the nursing staff all believe further intervention is futile and causing suffering. The patient has not been able to express her wishes for some time.",prompt1:"How should this be managed?",prompt2:"What is the ethical and human weight of a medical power of attorney — and what happens when the person holding it is making decisions the team believes are not in the patient's interests?"}
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a GP. Your receptionist tells you that a patient — a regular — has been posting negative reviews online, claiming you misdiagnosed them and that you were dismissive. You remember the consultation. You believe you acted appropriately. The patient is due in for an appointment next week.",prompt1:"How do you approach the upcoming appointment?",prompt2:"How should doctors respond to public criticism of their clinical care — and what does it mean to maintain a therapeutic relationship with a patient who has publicly attacked you?"}
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are on a hospital committee reviewing a complaint made by a patient's family about the care their father received in the ICU. The family alleges the team was dismissive and failed to explain treatment decisions. The senior intensivist — a highly respected clinician — is defensive and attributes the complaint to the family 'not understanding the complexity of the situation.' You have reviewed the notes and believe there were communication failures.",prompt1:"How do you navigate this committee meeting?",prompt2:"What makes it hard to hold senior clinicians accountable, and what systems should exist to make it easier?"}
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a junior doctor. A nurse approaches you and says she is not comfortable administering a medication you have prescribed — not because she believes it is clinically wrong, but because she has a 'feeling' something is off and can't explain it. She is an experienced nurse with a strong track record. There is no objective clinical reason to change the order.",prompt1:"How do you respond?",prompt2:"How much weight should clinical intuition carry — from an experienced nurse, from a junior doctor, from a specialist — and how should teams navigate this?"}
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a second-year medical student. A lecturer who runs a compulsory component of your program has been making comments in class that several students — including you — have found belittling, particularly toward students who answer questions incorrectly. One student has approached you privately and says she cried after the last session. No formal complaint has been made.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"What makes it particularly difficult for students to raise concerns about educators who hold power over their academic progression?"}
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a junior hospital doctor. You have been asked by your registrar to take over the care of a patient from a colleague who is going off shift. During handover, your colleague gives you information that contradicts what is documented in the patient's notes. When you point this out, your colleague becomes irritable and says 'just go with what I've told you, the notes are wrong.'",prompt1:"How do you manage this handover situation?",prompt2:"What are the patient safety risks embedded in poor clinical handover, and what would an ideal handover culture look like?"}
,{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a medical student on clinical placement. Your supervisor pulls you aside and tells you that one of your fellow students has raised a concern about your clinical performance — specifically that you seem uncertain and hesitant with patients. You were not aware of this and do not know which fellow student raised it.",prompt1:"How do you respond to your supervisor in this moment?",prompt2:"How do you process criticism that is anonymous, unspecific, and comes from a peer — and how do you determine whether it is worth acting on?"}

// POLICY (10)
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner says: 'Australia has one of the highest rates of antibiotic prescription in the developed world. This is contributing to antimicrobial resistance — a global crisis that some experts say is as serious a threat as climate change. What do you think needs to change, and at what level?'",prompt1:"What are the drivers of antibiotic overprescription, and what would an effective response look like?",prompt2:"How do you communicate risk to patients when the harm is systemic and diffuse rather than immediate and individual?"}
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'There is a growing movement to introduce a sugar tax in Australia — a levy on sugary drinks — as a public health measure to reduce obesity and type 2 diabetes. It has worked with variable success in other countries. What is your view?'",prompt1:"What are the arguments for and against a sugar tax as a public health intervention?",prompt2:"When is it appropriate for governments to use taxation to influence health behaviour — and where should the line be drawn?"}
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner presents this situation: 'A major Australian hospital is considering introducing a policy of mandatory drug and alcohol testing for all clinical staff before each shift. The policy has been proposed following two incidents involving impaired clinicians. Unions are strongly opposed.'",prompt1:"What are the key considerations for and against this policy?",prompt2:"How do you balance patient safety with the rights and wellbeing of healthcare workers?"}
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'Australia's Medicare system funds GP consultations at a rate that many argue is too low to sustain bulk billing, leading to out-of-pocket costs that are highest for the people who can least afford them. What do you think should happen?'",prompt1:"What are the systemic causes of declining bulk billing, and what would a fair solution look like?",prompt2:"How do you think about equity in healthcare access — and whose responsibility is it to ensure it?"}
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner says: 'There is an ongoing debate about whether voluntary assisted dying should be further expanded in Australia — including for people with treatment-resistant mental illness, not just terminal physical illness. What do you think?'",prompt1:"What are the strongest arguments on each side of this debate?",prompt2:"How do you hold a personal view on a deeply contested moral question while remaining able to practise ethically across a diverse patient population?"}
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'Preventive medicine — stopping disease before it starts — is consistently underfunded compared to acute care in Australia. Why do you think that is, and what would you do about it if you had meaningful influence over health policy?'",prompt1:"Why is preventive medicine chronically underfunded, and what are the structural barriers to changing that?",prompt2:"If you were advising a health minister, what one policy change would you prioritise and why?"}
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner presents this: 'Australia has a significant and well-documented gap in health outcomes between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Australians. This gap has persisted despite decades of policy attention. What do you think has gone wrong, and what do you think is actually required to close it?'",prompt1:"What are the root causes of the Indigenous health gap in Australia, and why have existing policies fallen short?",prompt2:"What does culturally safe care actually mean in practice — and what changes are required at the level of medical training and health systems?"}
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'Artificial intelligence is increasingly being used in medical diagnosis — in radiology, pathology, dermatology, and beyond. Some predict it will transform medicine fundamentally. What opportunities and risks do you see, and how should the medical profession respond?'",prompt1:"What are the most significant opportunities and risks of AI in clinical medicine?",prompt2:"What should NOT be delegated to AI in healthcare — and why?"}
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner says: 'Mental health services in Australia are chronically underfunded and inaccessible for many people, particularly outside major cities. At the same time, demand is increasing rapidly — especially among young people. What needs to change, and at what level?'",prompt1:"What are the structural barriers to mental health care access in Australia, and what solutions would address them?",prompt2:"How do you think about the relationship between individual clinical care and the social determinants that produce poor mental health outcomes?"}
,{category:"Policy",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'Medical practitioners are required by law to report certain conditions — including some communicable diseases, certain injuries, and impaired drivers — to authorities. Some argue these reporting obligations undermine patient trust and reduce help-seeking. Others say they are essential for public safety. What is your view?'",prompt1:"What is the ethical basis for mandatory reporting obligations in medicine — and where are they justified?",prompt2:"How do mandatory reporting obligations affect the doctor-patient relationship, and how should clinicians manage that tension in practice?"}

];
